Interpolation and Variables

This lesson explains how variable substitution works in Maven and the variables that come default with Maven.

Maven allows using predefined and user-defined variables in a POM file. This avoids repeating values across child POMs and also makes modifications easy as any change only needs to be applied at one place.

Any elements with a single value present in the project model (the XSD that defines the structure of a POM file) can be accessed using the prefix project.. For instance, we can access the version of the project using project.version. Similarly, if we want to access the default value of the source directory defined in the super POM, we can do so using the expression project.build.sourceDirectory. Some of the variables are special, i.e., not defined in the POM or super POM, such as project.basedir and maven.build.timestamp.

Users can define their own variables as properties under the properties XML element and can then use the variable as ＄{X} where X is the name of the property. Properties defined in a parent POM can also be used in a child POM. With this backdrop let’s dive into the exercise below which will give us hands-on exposure to using properties in POM.

# Change directory to Project7
cd /Project7
# Examine the parent project's POM file. Note the artifactId is set to
# <artifactId>project7-${project.organization.name}-${project.packaging}</artifactId>
# We made-up the artifactId name to demonstrate the use of properties.
cat /Project7/pom.xml
# Now build the parent project. The artifact produced will be project7-DataJek-pom-1.pom.
# The values for the properties ${project.organization.name} and 
# ${project.packaging} will be substituted.
mvn install
# Now change directory to the child project
cd Child
# Examine the child's POM file. Observe we want to name the child artifact
# as <artifactId>project7a-${maven.build.timestamp}-${MyString}</artifactId>
# The artifact name includes the build timestamp as well as a user-defined
# property MyString. Note that the property MyString is defined in the parent
# POM and commented out for now in the child POM.
cat pom.xml
# Build the child project
mvn install
# Examine the artifact produced which will be named 
# project7a-2020-07-21-OrdinaryDev-1a.jar. The property MyString is substituted
# for the value OrdinaryDev coming from the parent POM.
ls /root/.m2/repository/io/datajek/project7a-2020-07-21-OrdinaryDev/1a/
#

In the above exercise the parent POM defines artifactId as:

<artifactId>project7-＄{project.organization.name}-＄{project.packaging}</artifactId>

We use the pre-defined variable project.organization.name which is set to the value DataJek, and the variable project.packaging which is set to the value pom in the artifactId name. The resulting artifactId is project7-DataJek-pom-1.pom.

Next, we build the child project where the artifactId is set as:

<artifactId>project7a-＄{maven.build.timestamp}-＄{MyString}</artifactId>

We include the build timestamp and the variable MyString in the artifactId. Initially, MyString is inherited from the parent POM and the name of the artifact produced is project7a-2020-07-21-OrdinaryDev-1a.jar.

Next, we uncomment the property MyString in the parent POM and re-build the child project. This time the value for the property MyString is picked up from the child POM and the artifact produced is named project7a-2020-07-21-SuperDev-1a.jar as shown below.

This exercise creates concocted artifact names in order to demonstrate the use of user-defined and predefined properties. Maven also allows for use of other properties listed below:

  1. Environment variables can be accessed using the prefix env., for instance ＄{env.PATH} will access the PATH variable.

  2. Elements in the settings.xml file (discussed later) can be accessed using the prefix settings., for instance ＄{settings.offline}.

  3. Java system properties returned by the snippet java.lang.System.getProperties() can also be accessed as POM properties using the java. prefix, for instance ＄{java.home}.
